<hint><p>
Given the position of a particle, you can find its velocity.
</p></hint>
<answer><p>
<m>|t|</m>
</p></answer>
<solution><p>
Given the position of the particle, we can find its velocity:
<me>
\vv(t)=\vr'(t)=(\cos t, -\sin t , 1)</me>
</p>

<p>Applying the given formula,
<me>
\vL(t)=\vr \times \vv=(\sin t , \cos t , t) \times (\cos t, -\sin t , 1).</me>
</p>

<p><ul>
<li>[<alert>Solution 1:</alert>]
We can first compute the cross product, then differentiate:
<md>
<mrow>
\vL(t)&amp; = (\cos t + t\sin t)\vi + (t\cos t - \sin t)\vj-\vk
</mrow><mrow>
\vL'(t)&amp;=t\cos t\,\vi -t\sin t\, \vj
</mrow><mrow>
|\vL'(t)|&amp;=\sqrt{t^2(\sin^2 t + \cos^2 t)}=\sqrt{t^2}=|t|
</mrow>
</md>
</li>
<li>[<alert>Solution 2:</alert>]
